<p>Fake Google reviews cost real money. Each additional star rating increases local business revenue by <a href="https://wiserreview.com/blog/fake-review-statistics/">5-9%</a>. A fake 1-star review that drops your average from 4.8 to 4.5 can cost thousands in lost customers. Google removed <a href="https://www.seroundtable.com/google-maps-spam-fighting-2024-39186.html">240 million policy-violating reviews in 2024</a>. That is a 40% increase over 2023. The problem is growing.</p>
<p>Most business owners do not know how to handle fake Google reviews. They either ignore them (which damages rankings and trust) or respond emotionally (which makes things worse). Neither approach removes the review or protects the business.</p>
<p>We have helped businesses across 70+ industries manage their online reputation. This guide walks through the exact 7-step process to identify, report, respond to, and remove fake Google reviews.</p>
<p>Here is what you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>How to identify whether a review is actually fake</li>
<li>The exact process to report fake reviews to Google</li>
<li>How to respond publicly without making the situation worse</li>
<li>Escalation options when Google does not remove the review</li>
<li>Legal remedies available for defamatory fake reviews</li>
<li>How to build a review strategy that buries fake reviews with real ones</li>
</ul>
<h2>Step 1: Identify Whether the Review Is Actually Fake</h2>
<p>Not every negative review is fake. Before reporting, confirm that the review violates <a href="https://support.google.com/contributionpolicy/answer/7400114">Google's review policies</a>. Google removes reviews that violate policy. Google does not remove reviews just because they are negative.</p>
<h3>Signs of a Fake Review</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>No record of the reviewer as a customer.</strong> Check your CRM, appointment system, and transaction records. If the name does not match any customer, the review may be fake.</li>
<li><strong>The reviewer has zero or few other reviews.</strong> Accounts created solely to leave one negative review are a red flag.</li>
<li><strong>The review mentions services you do not offer.</strong> A dental office receiving a review about "terrible food" is clearly fake or posted to the wrong business.</li>
<li><strong>Multiple negative reviews appear at the same time.</strong> A cluster of 1-star reviews within 24-48 hours suggests a coordinated attack, often from a competitor.</li>
<li><strong>The review contains no specific details.</strong> "Terrible experience. Would not recommend." with no description of what happened is common in fake reviews.</li>
<li><strong>The reviewer is a known competitor or disgruntled employee.</strong> Check if the reviewer's profile links to a competing business.</li>
</ul>
<h3>What Does Not Count as Fake</h3>
<ul>
<li>A real customer leaving a negative review because they had a bad experience</li>
<li>A customer who exaggerates their complaint</li>
<li>A review with factual errors about your business (unless it is clearly not your customer)</li>
</ul>
<p>Google will not remove a genuine negative review, even if you disagree with it. Save your reporting efforts for reviews that actually violate policy. For strategies to get more legitimate positive reviews, read our guide on <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">how to get more Google reviews</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> Reporting legitimate negative reviews as fake wastes time and can flag your account to Google for abuse of the reporting system.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="How to identify fake Google reviews with 6 warning signs" src="/images/blog/fake-review-warning-signs.webp" /></p>
<h2>Step 2: Flag the Review Through Google Business Profile</h2>
<p>Once you confirm a review is fake, report it directly through your <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile</a>.</p>
<h3>How to Flag a Review</h3>
<ol>
<li>Sign in to your Google Business Profile at business.google.com</li>
<li>Find the review you want to report</li>
<li>Click the 3-dot menu next to the review</li>
<li>Select "Report review"</li>
<li>Choose the reason that best matches the violation:</li>
<li><strong>Off-topic</strong> (review is not about your business)</li>
<li><strong>Spam</strong> (fake or promotional content)</li>
<li><strong>Conflict of interest</strong> (competitor or employee)</li>
<li><strong>Profanity</strong> (contains offensive language)</li>
<li><strong>Bullying or harassment</strong></li>
<li><strong>Discrimination or hate speech</strong></li>
<li><strong>Personal information</strong> (contains private data)</li>
<li>Submit the report</li>
</ol>
<h3>What Happens After Flagging</h3>
<p>Google reviews reports manually. Response times range from 3 days to 3 weeks. Google does not notify you of the outcome in most cases. The review either disappears or stays. Check back in 7-14 days.</p>
<p>You can flag a review only once from your GBP dashboard. Multiple flags from the same account do not speed up the process and may be flagged as spam.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> Flagging is the fastest official removal method. Most fake reviews that clearly violate policy get removed within 1-2 weeks through this process.</p>
<h2>Step 3: Respond to the Fake Review Publicly</h2>
<p>While waiting for Google to process your report, respond to the review publicly. This response is not for the fake reviewer. It is for every potential customer who reads it.</p>
<h3>How to Respond to a Fake Review</h3>
<p><strong>Do:</strong>
- Stay professional and calm
- State that you cannot find any record of them as a customer
- Invite them to contact you directly to resolve the issue
- Keep the response under 100 words</p>
<p><strong>Do not:</strong>
- Accuse the reviewer of lying (even if they are)
- Get emotional or defensive
- Share any customer information
- Threaten legal action publicly</p>
<h3>Response Template for Fake Reviews</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>"Thank you for your feedback. We take all reviews seriously. We have searched our records and cannot find any appointment or transaction under this name. If you are a customer, please contact us at [phone/email] so we can look into this further and resolve your concern."</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This response accomplishes 3 things:</p>
<ol>
<li>It signals to potential customers that you take feedback seriously</li>
<li>It subtly flags the review as potentially fake without making accusations</li>
<li>It gives the fake reviewer no ammunition to escalate</li>
</ol>
<p>Use our <a href="/tools/review-response-generator/">review response generator</a> to craft professional responses quickly.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> <a href="https://wiserreview.com/blog/fake-review-statistics/">82% of consumers have read a fake review in the past year</a>, and 74% cannot always distinguish real from fake. A professional response to a fake review builds trust even if the review remains visible.</p>
