<h3>How to Escalate Effectively</h3>
<p>When contacting support, provide:</p>
<ul>
<li>Your business name and GBP listing URL</li>
<li>The specific review URL (right-click the review timestamp to copy the link)</li>
<li>The policy violation (be specific: "spam," "conflict of interest," "off-topic")</li>
<li>Evidence that the reviewer is not a customer (CRM records, appointment logs)</li>
<li>Any patterns (multiple fake reviews from similar accounts, competitor connection)</li>
</ul>
<p>Be factual. Be specific. Do not rant. Support agents process hundreds of requests daily. Clear, evidence-based reports get resolved faster than emotional complaints.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> Many fake reviews that survive initial flagging get removed after human review through support channels. The escalation adds a second layer of evaluation.</p>
<h2>Step 5: Document Everything for Legal Action</h2>
<p>If Google does not remove the review after escalation, and the review contains defamatory statements, document everything for potential legal action.</p>
<h3>What to Document</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Screenshot of the review with timestamp</li>
<li>[ ] The reviewer's Google profile (name, photo, other reviews)</li>
<li>[ ] Your CRM/appointment records showing no matching customer</li>
<li>[ ] Any evidence linking the review to a competitor or known individual</li>
<li>[ ] Timeline of your reporting and escalation attempts</li>
<li>[ ] The review's impact on your business (lost customers, revenue decline)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Legal Options</h3>
<p><strong>Important legal context:</strong> The <a href="https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/news/press-releases/2024/08/federal-trade-commission-announces-final-rule-banning-fake-reviews-testimonials">FTC's 2024 rule on fake reviews</a> makes creating, selling, or buying fake reviews punishable by civil penalties up to $53,088 per violation. The FTC issued its first warning letters to 10 companies in December 2025. This gives businesses legal backing when pursuing fake reviewers.</p>
<p><strong>Cease and desist letter:</strong> A lawyer sends a formal letter demanding the reviewer remove the defamatory content. Cost: $500-$2,000. This works when the reviewer is identifiable and the statements are provably false.</p>
<p><strong>Defamation lawsuit:</strong> For reviews that contain demonstrably false statements of fact (not opinions) that cause measurable financial harm. Cost: $5,000-$50,000+. This is a last resort for serious cases where the fake review causes significant damage.</p>
<p><strong>Court order for removal:</strong> A court can order Google to remove a review if it is found to be defamatory. Google complies with valid court orders. Cost: Included in the lawsuit.</p>
<p><strong>Important distinction:</strong> Opinions are protected speech. "I did not like the service" is an opinion. "This dentist uses expired anesthetics" is a statement of fact. Only false statements of fact qualify as defamation. Consult a lawyer before pursuing legal action.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> Legal documentation protects your options. Even if you never file a lawsuit, having organized evidence strengthens future escalation attempts with Google.</p>
<h2>Step 6: Bury Fake Reviews With Real Ones</h2>
<p>The fastest way to reduce the impact of fake reviews is to generate a steady flow of real positive reviews. A business with 5 reviews and 1 fake 1-star has a 4.2 average. A business with 200 reviews and 1 fake 1-star has a 4.9 average.</p>
<h3>How to Generate More Real Reviews</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Ask every satisfied customer.</strong> After a completed service, ask in person: "Would you mind leaving us a Google review?" In-person requests convert at 70%+.</li>
<li><strong>Send a follow-up text or email.</strong> Include a direct link to your Google review page. Make leaving a review a 2-tap process.</li>
<li><strong>Use a QR code.</strong> Print a QR code on receipts, table tents, or business cards linking directly to your review page.</li>
<li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Businesses that respond to reviews get 35% more reviews than those that do not.</li>
<li><strong>Time your asks.</strong> Ask immediately after a positive interaction, not 2 weeks later.</li>
</ul>
<p>A review velocity of 10-20 new reviews per month dilutes any fake review within weeks. For a detailed review strategy, read our complete guide on <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">getting more Google reviews</a>.</p>
<p>For tools to manage reviews at scale, see our <a href="/best/review-management-tools/">review management tools guide</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> You cannot control whether Google removes a fake review. You can control how many real reviews surround it. Volume is the best defense.</p>
